<paragraph blockId="7.[192,1442,803,1033]" pageId="7" pageNumber="6">
This is a common and widespread species, found throughout most of 
<collectingCountry box="[1041,1126,803,829]" name="Mexico" pageId="7" pageNumber="6">Mexico</collectingCountry>
. We are aware of specimens of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Hope" baseAuthorityYear="1840" box="[222,348,837,863]" class="Insecta" family="Rutelidae" genus="Chrysina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="6" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="adelaida">
<emphasis box="[222,348,837,863]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="6">C. adelaida</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from every state of 
<collectingCountry box="[575,658,837,863]" name="Mexico" pageId="7" pageNumber="6">Mexico</collectingCountry>
north of the Isthmus of Tehuantepec except 
<collectingRegion box="[1165,1335,837,863]" country="Mexico" name="Baja California" pageId="7" pageNumber="6">Baja California</collectingRegion>
and 
<collectingRegion country="Mexico" name="Baja California Sur" pageId="7" pageNumber="6">Baja California Sur</collectingRegion>
. It has been found in pine-oak forests at elevations between 1300 and 3000 meters above sea level. Numerous specimens have been found in the Sierra Azul in Santa Inés del Monte at 
<quantity box="[1138,1224,905,931]" metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.3" pageId="7" pageNumber="6" unit="m" value="2300.0">2300 m</quantity>
, and in the vicinity of Santiago Clavellinas (2100–2300 and 
<quantity box="[636,720,938,965]" metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.745" pageId="7" pageNumber="6" unit="m" value="2745.0">2745 m</quantity>
) in pine-oak forests (
<specimenCount box="[956,1042,938,965]" pageId="7" pageNumber="6" type="male">5 males</specimenCount>
and 
<specimenCount box="[1095,1201,938,965]" pageId="7" pageNumber="6" type="female">4 females</specimenCount>
) during August–September 2018 and 
<date box="[392,500,972,998]" pageId="7" pageNumber="6" value="2019-07">July 2019</date>
. There are several common color morphs of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Hope" baseAuthorityYear="1840" box="[1013,1140,972,999]" class="Insecta" family="Rutelidae" genus="Chrysina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="6" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="adelaida">
<emphasis box="[1013,1140,972,999]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="6">C. adelaida</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from reddish striped (
<figureCitation captionStart="Figures 1–9" captionStartId="4.[192,279,831,857]" captionTargetBox="[243,1383,223,792]" captionTargetId="figure-449@4.[240,1392,213,801]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="Figures 1–9. Dorsal and ventral habitus of adult Chrysina specimens (1×). 1–2) C. clavellina Holotype male. 3–4) C. clavellina female. 5) C. lacordairei. 6) C. adelaida red morph. 7) C. adelaida green morph. 8) C. expansa. 9) C. adolphi." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4565329" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4565329/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="6">Fig. 6</figureCitation>
) to mostly green (
<figureCitation box="[411,477,1006,1033]" captionStart="Figures 1–9" captionStartId="4.[192,279,831,857]" captionTargetBox="[243,1383,223,792]" captionTargetId="figure-449@4.[240,1392,213,801]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="Figures 1–9. Dorsal and ventral habitus of adult Chrysina specimens (1×). 1–2) C. clavellina Holotype male. 3–4) C. clavellina female. 5) C. lacordairei. 6) C. adelaida red morph. 7) C. adelaida green morph. 8) C. expansa. 9) C. adolphi." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4565329" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4565329/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="6">Fig. 7</figureCitation>
). Adults of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Hope" baseAuthorityYear="1840" box="[604,729,1006,1032]" class="Insecta" family="Rutelidae" genus="Chrysina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="6" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="adelaida">
<emphasis box="[604,729,1006,1032]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="6">C. adelaida</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are known to feed on the needles of pine trees (
<taxonomicName box="[1261,1323,1007,1032]" class="Pinopsida" family="Pinaceae" genus="Pinus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Pinales" pageId="7" pageNumber="6" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1261,1323,1007,1032]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="6">Pinus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species).
</paragraph>
